(350, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '01a6b8957cdfdf7a8baa7f1936fc9505', 'Enter a numeric value for the number of rows in your textarea. This will only affect the following option types: CSS, Textarea, & Textarea Simple.', 0),
(351, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '4079b1ca4a9a54e6f13cf806b063c622', 'Post Type', 0),
(352, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '9582effebbfc2ceca17b21f713994861', 'Add a comma separated list of post type like <code>post,page</code>. This will only affect the following option types: Custom Post Type Checkbox, & Custom Post Type Select. Below are the default post types available with WordPress and that are also compatible with OptionTree. You can also add your own custom <code>post_type</code>. At this time <code>any</code> does not seem to return results properly and is something I plan on looking into.', 0),
(353, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '30d10883c017c4fd6751c8982e20dae1', 'Taxonomy', 0),
(354, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'f1842b9db1b2e6040f62e01019a6f1a8', 'Add a comma separated list of any registered taxonomy like <code>category,post_tag</code>. This will only affect the following option types: Taxonomy Checkbox, & Taxonomy Select.', 0),
(355, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '7022ceebf78da53364906c4868daf99d', 'Min, Max, & Step', 0),
(356, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'ca49cf7e872094fe34426df26c592cfb', 'Add a comma separated list of options in the following format <code>0,100,1</code> (slide from <code>0-100</code> in intervals of <code>1</code>). The three values represent the minimum, maximum, and step options and will only affect the Numeric Slider option type.', 0),
(357, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'ee0b618faab3aafbb457b4a0c57dd954', 'CSS Class', 0),
(358, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '0f29f2d7a4e8e6a587e1f601a11ad5d0', 'Add and optional class to any option type.', 0),
(359, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'a9ded1e5ce5d75814730bb4caaf49419', 'Background', 0),
(360, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '98a6c4b572fe559dd187dc4a272d0c98', 'The Background option type is for adding background styles to your theme either dynamically via the CSS option type below or manually with <code>ot_get_option()</code>. Background has filters that allow you to change the defaults. For example, you can filter on <code>ot_recognized_background_repeat</code>, <code>ot_recognized_background_attachment</code>, and <code>ot_recognized_background_position</code>. These filters allow you to fine tune the select lists for your specific CSS needs.', 0),
(361, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '36bb70a1e14bfc6d6c322c27374b6550', 'Category Select', 0),
(362, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'cd01a3e482f21904a3c5ab838bd99b1d', 'The Category Select option type displays a list of category IDs. It allows the user to select only one category ID and will return that value for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(363, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '46198d837a3e0f2520037c26e8d05b3c', 'Category Checkbox', 0),
(364, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '57c793dd615467d3e03341385644ff18', 'The Category Checkbox option type displays a list of category IDs. It allows the user to check multiple category IDs and will return that value as an array for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(365, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '4f8222964f9a317cef99dddc23a121bd', 'Checkbox', 0),
(366, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'b06ae588dd51f45ac1829a8aa4278d31', 'The Checkbox option type is fairly self explanatory. Typically used to ask questions. For example, "Do you want to activate asynchronous Google analytics?" would be a single checkbox with a value of yes. You could have more complex usages but the idea is that you can easily grab the value of the checkbox and use it in you theme. In this situation you would test if the checkbox has a value and execute a block of code if it does and do nothing if it doesn''t.', 0),
(367, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'b31cc161a958b6f2e132587a044c63ca', 'Colorpicker', 0),
(368, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '3f6f38f4b1dcbcd16745f57bf77f70a0', 'The Colorpicker option type saves a hexadecimal color code for use in CSS. Use it to modify the color of something in your theme.', 0),
(369, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '2c56c360580420d293172f42d85dfbed', 'CSS', 0),
(370, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '97068a658af7478c43a9766433cc8c14', 'The CSS option type is a textarea that when used properly can add dynamic CSS to your theme from within OptionTree. Unfortunately, due server limitations you will need to create a file named <code>dynamic.css</code> at the root level of your theme and change permissions using chmod so the server can write to the file. I have had the most success setting this single file to 0777 but feel free to play around with permissions until everything is working. A good starting point is 0666. When the server can save to the file CSS will automatically be updated each time you save your theme options.', 0),
(371, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'f51f103c464db3cf83c13e4541168a4f', 'An example of the CSS option type: This assumes you have an option with the ID of <code>custom_background_css</code> which will display the saved values for that option.', 0),
(372, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '324118a6721dd6b8a9b9f4e327df2bf5', 'Input', 0),
(373, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '29c2c02a361c9d7028472e5d92cd4a54', 'Output', 0),
(374, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '28d318449b4eee2d3b6dd73331b7e854', 'Custom Post Type Select', 0),
(375, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '5ad3dab8da84ab11bca9a18cbb5fd410', 'The Custom Post Type Select option type displays a list of IDs from any available WordPress post type or custom post type. It will return a single post ID for use in a custom function or loop. Requires at least one valid <code>post_type</code> when created in the settings. For some reason <code>any</code> does not work correctly and will looked into in future version.', 0),
(376, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '0af8578e11bb977f2b46e372fe32e5b1', 'Custom Post Type Checkbox', 0),
(377, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '369326573822dda1e4c7e119621a7e7e', 'The Custom Post Type Select option type displays a list of IDs from any available WordPress post type or custom post type. It allows the user to check multiple post IDs for use in a custom function or loop. Requires at least one valid <code>post_type</code> when created in the settings. For some reason <code>any</code> does not work correctly and will looked into in future version.', 0),
(378, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '3f7b121ec5cc19cf6676a28656e0d5b8', 'List Item', 0),
(379, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'a537193088a89080d159c9ae416ef5de', 'The list Item replaced the old Slider option type. It allows for a great deal of customization. You can add settings to the List Item and those settings will be displayed to the user when they add a new List Item. Typical use is for creating sliding content or blocks of code for custom layouts.', 0),
(380, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '911842b19d8b2f9bbed8cfe909d52975', 'Measurement', 0),
(381, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '94d96b9481400526724b8bfd62207195', 'The Measurement option type is a mix of input and select fields. The text input excepts a value and the select lets you choose the unit of measurement to add to that value. Currently the default units are <code>px</code>, <code>%</code>, <code>em</code>, <code>pt</code>. However, you can change them with the <code>ot_measurement_unit_types</code> filter.', 0),
(382, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '41f5ae8cb74da9785a364c59b8cebfa2', 'Example filter to add new units to the Measurement option type. Added to <code>functions.php</code>.', 0),
(383, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'ed9911c251cc1ab76edf25e9dd811fb2', 'Example filter to completely change the units in the Measurement option type. Added to <code>functions.php</code>.', 0),
(384, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'd1a4f66444ce1a06fdf7f9611c8fc613', 'Numeric Slider', 0),
(385, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '282d97cc26beb0aaf00345a0225111f2', 'The Numeric Slider option type displays a jQuery UI slider. It will return a single numerical value for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(386, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '25eb0d238b3aed4348feb7f807ad9fe4', 'Page Select', 0),
(387, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'e12596a5e60855063fa4a0c18bf86aa8', 'The Page Select option type displays a list of page IDs. It will return a single page ID for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(388, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '91b66fb0338eb9c08e021276dbf144c1', 'Page Checkbox', 0),
(389, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '2153c0865e6c75b4b8fe21d7a8e20240', 'The Page Select option type displays a list of page IDs. It allows the user to check multiple page IDs for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(390, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '989ec039711b27da7a7cb691584c55b5', 'Post Select', 0),
(391, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '3270db542dd6b7b7062d174a4dc3a40b', 'The Post Select option type displays a list of post IDs. It will return a single post ID for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(392, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'f2277e8b85f3ccf2c1f155e2fd2ea3fe', 'Post Checkbox', 0),
(393, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '2e003e594cd1f39c99fc5c341de15e0b', 'The Post Select option type displays a list of post IDs. It allows the user to check multiple post IDs for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(394, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '1f32d2c1b49b9b0c9d99bd10da107e41', 'Radio', 0),
(395, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'cb09d51deb3330aa0017ac6f0d55d6ac', 'The Radio option type could ask a question. For example, "Do you want to activate the custom navigation?" could require a yes or no answer with a radio option. In this situation you would test if the radio has a value of ''yes'' and execute a block of code, or if it''s ''no'' execute a different block of code.', 0),
(396, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '5a027050bc6c3a4e66ddeb51d5fc8446', 'Radio Image', 0),
(397, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '50d28f555c56dbd8b4ac21377a3c6238', 'the Radio Images option type is primarily used for layouts. However, you can filter the image list using <code>ot_radio_images</code>. As well, you can add your own custom images using the choices array.', 0),
(398, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'fa1626c2cb852edb1f60b89f7120219f', 'This example executes the <code>ot_radio_images</code> filter on layout images attached to the <code>my_radio_images</code> field. Added to <code>functions.php</code>.', 0),
(399, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'e0626222614bdee31951d84c64e5e9ff', 'Select', 0),
(400, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '519612551dbad85cca25e0e8d8286781', 'The Select option type is used to list anything you want that would be chosen from a select list.', 0),
(401, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '14fefd829650efff413a372aa0cb6013', 'Sidebar Select', 0),
(402, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '55fe2b0c4e3272c86e23e627aab8be02', 'This option type makes it possible for users to select a WordPress registered sidebar to use on a specific area. By using the two provided filters, <code>ot_recognized_sidebars</code>, and <code>ot_recognized_sidebars_{$field_id}</code> we can be selective about which sidebars are available on a specific content area.', 0),
(403, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '336a44c11d59e8a64f8dd2a2108e882b', 'For example, if we create a WordPress theme that provides the ability to change the Blog Sidebar and we don''t want to have the footer sidebars available on this area, we can unset those sidebars either manually or by using a regular expression if we have a common name like <code>footer-sidebar-$i</code>.', 0),
(404, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '2d9b9a764fb0be4be10e1b2fce63f561', 'Slider', 0),
(405, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '969425dcc003ae133bf585b88abce418', 'The Slider option type is technically deprecated. Use the List Item option type instead, as it''s infinitely more customizable. Typical use is for creating sliding image content.', 0),
(406, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '35306a5617c975bb0b5471594652f19a', 'Tag Checkbox', 0),
(407, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'c5846f4acaf4d1135c41e7cfd4fcc71d', 'The Tag Checkbox option type displays a list of tag IDs. It allows the user to check multiple tag IDs and will return that value as an array for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(408, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '0bdb5986df4b47cba27daee0cc754b10', 'Tag Select', 0),
(409, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '01f14113ba66a8d06fa88addfef2723e', 'The Tag Select option type displays a list of tag IDs. It allows the user to select only one tag ID and will return that value for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(410, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'b8c15f1715e54279ff7986666d0f5442', 'Taxonomy Checkbox', 0),
(411, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '39502ffece8e50265a53c697611f604b', 'The Taxonomy Checkbox option type displays a list of taxonomy IDs. It allows the user to check multiple taxonomy IDs and will return that value as an array for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(412, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '1d38a177b3002399973c97e2b2bea99e', 'Taxonomy Select', 0),
(413, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '2b4c163c75d06b08291a21973d5617c9', 'The Taxonomy Select option type displays a list of taxonomy IDs. It allows the user to select only one taxonomy ID and will return that value for use in a custom function or loop.', 0),
(414, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '54c01e25cf8398ce0ea27b327a5d8914', 'Text (Input)', 0),
(415, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'cc134d92455f7658d1468f7340909272', 'The Text option type would be used to save a string value. For example, a link to feedburner, your Twitter username, or Google Analytics ID are all good candidates. Any optional or required text that is of reasonably short character length.', 0),
(416, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'b5d4d25fe3fa9f8263b5f279a372b709', 'Textarea', 0),
(417, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '9ee60924f2d568af7147b7cba3f18dad', 'The Textarea option type is a large string value used for custom code or text in the theme. The new Textarea has a WYSIWYG editor that can be filtered to change the buttons shown. For example, you can filter on <code>wpautop</code>, <code>media_buttons</code>, <code>tinymce</code>, and <code>quicktags</code>.', 0),
(418, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '0ae424c45d08b08b2582deb033548e2a', 'Example filters to alter the Textarea option type. Added to <code>functions.php</code>.', 0),
(419, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '58af517d1affceb4c2b2c2d43d9fc7a9', 'This example keeps WordPress from executing the <code>wpautop</code> filter on the line breaks. The default is <code>true</code> which means it wraps line breaks with an HTML <code>p</code> tag.', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_icl_strings` (`id`, `language`, `context`, `name`, `value`, `status`) VALUES
(420, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'ff87eef7c279ff74b5ff582a1b1777fe', 'This example keeps WordPress from executing the <code>media_buttons</code> filter on the textarea WYSIWYG. The default is <code>true</code> which means show the buttons.', 0),
(421, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '243e79d423fe380fae5013c4b19927f6', 'This example keeps WordPress from executing the <code>tinymce</code> filter on the textarea WYSIWYG. The default is <code>true</code> which means show the tinymce.', 0),
(422, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '41284fd7aed0f0125098e3e0b8df78a5', 'This example alters the <code>quicktags</code> filter on the textarea WYSIWYG. The default is <code>array( ''buttons'' => ''strong,em,link,block,del,ins,img,ul,ol,li,code,spell,close'' )</code> which means show those quicktags. It also means you can filter in your own custom quicktags.', 0),
(423, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'dc517d6ef758acc18bf8e4a154589396', 'Textarea Simple', 0),
(424, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '71664f456fe7efb97d4480ba3f1a4ff2', 'The Textarea Simple option type is a large string value used for custom code or text in the theme. The new Textarea Simple does not have a WYSIWYG editor. But you can still filter on <code>wpautop</code>.', 0),
(425, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '9bdd2d72e651baaa5e387057511fa4ce', 'This example tells WordPress to execute the <code>wpautop</code> filter on the line breaks. The default is <code>false</code> which means it does not wraps line breaks with an HTML <code>p</code> tag. Added to <code>functions.php</code>.', 0),
(426, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '82797ef0b9e30134703b901f89dffffb', 'Textblock', 0),
(427, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '9e72ec3c38134ea2ee95dbc74498e434', 'The Textblock option type is used only on the Theme Option page. It will allow you to create & display HTML on your Theme Options page but has no title above the text block. You can then use the Textblock to add a more detailed set of instruction on how the options are used in your theme. You would NEVER use this in your themes template files as it does not save a value.', 0),
(428, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '2d0a806781e12fa9b59bf54a67bf4935', 'Textblock Titled', 0),
(429, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'f607eb13e2c6c82ba3e1d8da445949bc', 'The Textblock Titled option type is used only on the Theme Option page. It will allow you to create & display HTML on your Theme Options page and has a title above the text block. You can then use the Textblock Titled to add a more detailed set of instruction on how the options are used in your theme. You would NEVER use this in your themes template files as it does not save a value.', 0),
(430, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '603850e072131401265c4fc01027db93', 'Typography', 0),
(431, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '598593b82334f9254d746c04cc0cade6', 'The Typography option type is for adding typographic styles to your theme either dynamically via the CSS option type below or manually with <code>ot_get_option()</code>. Typography has filters that allow you to change the defaults. For example, you can filter on <code>ot_recognized_font_styles</code>, <code>ot_recognized_font_weights</code>, <code>ot_recognized_font_variants</code>, and <code>ot_recognized_font_families</code>. These filters allow you to fine tune the select lists for your specific CSS needs. The most important one though is <code>ot_recognized_font_families</code> as you can add your Google Fonts to create custom font stacks.', 0),
(432, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '090e544c131bead358106d491cc9d734', 'This example would filter <code>ot_recognized_font_families</code> to build your own font stack. Added to <code>functions.php</code>.', 0),
(433, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '91412465ea9169dfd901dd5e7c96dd99', 'Upload', 0),
(434, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '11e48a3028a2072a75c588b5696ab184', 'The Upload option type is used to upload any WordPress supported media. After uploading, users are required to press the "Send to OptionTree" button in order to populate the input with the URI of that media. There is one caveat of this feature. If you import the theme options and have uploaded media on one site the old URI will not reflect the URI of your new site. You''ll have to re-upload or FTP any media to your new server and change the URIs if necessary.', 0),
