(490, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '8420a6598ce542201f62ea4819707927', 'There are a few simple steps you need to take in order to use OptionTree''s built in Meta Box API. In the code below I''ll show you a basic demo of how to create your very own custom meta box using any number of the option types you have at your disposal. If you would like to see some demo code, there is a directory named <code>theme-mode</code> inside the <code>assets</code> directory that contains a file named <code>demo-meta-boxes.php</code> you can reference.', 0),
(491, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'a3970afc1af7610ea053fee465f00315', 'It''s important to note that Meta Boxes do not support WYSIWYG editors at this time and if you set one of your options to Textarea it will automatically revert to a Textarea Simple until a valid solution is found. WordPress released this statement regarding the wp_editor() function:', 0),
(492, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '07198aec131e9a87020fc2c5f520a8a2', 'Once instantiated, the WYSIWYG editor cannot be moved around in the DOM. What this means in practical terms, is that you cannot put it in meta-boxes that can be dragged and placed elsewhere on the page.', 0),
(493, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'a5458732ff53f24a818e0fd73c145d00', 'Create and include your custom meta boxes file.', 0),
(494, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '865c96edc72506eee157b30784461844', 'Create a file and name it anything you want, maybe <code>meta-boxes.php</code>.', 0),
(495, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '6bcb90d0ebd4ee21a0a877c36ed93c2f', 'As well, you''ll probably want to create a directory named <code>includes</code> to put your <code>meta-boxes.php</code> into which will help keep you file structure nice and tidy.', 0),
(496, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'b8a4e20153ba842a767fae96461199ce', 'Add the following code to your <code>functions.php</code>.', 0),
(497, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '576b3c5cec93748d0768dd3704256e17', 'Add a variation of the following code to your <code>meta-boxes.php</code>. You''ll obviously need to fill it in with all your custom array values. It''s important to note here that we use the <code>admin_init</code> filter because if you were to call the <code>ot_register_meta_box</code> function before OptionTree was loaded the sky would fall on your head.', 0),
(498, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '88553075c34b873757e218e54ede8182', 'There are a few simple steps you need to take in order to use OptionTree as a theme included module. In the code below I''ll show you a basic demo of how to include the entire plugin as a module, which will allow you to have the most up-to-date version of OptionTree without ever needing to hack the core of the plugin. If you would like to see some demo code, there is a directory named <code>theme-mode</code> inside the <code>assets</code> directory that contains a file named <code>demo-theme-options.php</code> you can reference.', 0),
(499, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '2509c0691f46ff50fabe4fda3f6666a6', 'Step 1: Include the plugin & turn on theme mode.', 0),
(500, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'c9f40a55fa241d3d61c20c74d49c8f6e', 'Download the latest version of <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/option-tree/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">OptionTree</a>.', 0),
(501, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '1ba2a81de12f81c4ad79f1071e45524a', 'Unpack the ZIP archive.', 0),
(502, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'cc5db33774498e8c59a02a049fce1bfd', 'Put the <code>option-tree</code> directory in the root of your theme. For example, the server path would be <code>/wp-content/themes/theme-name/option-tree/</code>.', 0),
(503, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'de62d9f7eda96b34a48d10597284c8fe', 'Add the following code to the beginning of your <code>functions.php</code>.', 0),
(504, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'd69877a83fca8f60b35c27a183eca3ab', 'It''s that simple! You now have OptionTree built into your theme and anytime there''s an update to the plugin you just replace the old version and you''re good to go..', 0),
(505, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '8d4ca667f7dcc8978363633cae9b305f', 'Step 2: Create Theme Options without using the UI Builder.', 0),
(506, 'en', 'theme option-tree', 'a61e216392d138f90286cafcfcca8420', 'Create a file and name it anything you want, maybe <code>theme-options.php</code>, or use the built in file export to create it for you. Remember, you should always check the file for errors before including it in your theme.', 0),
(507, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '341f9c6caa2f0b88239d2a3e73d5f38d', 'As well, you''ll probably want to create a directory named <code>includes</code> to put your <code>theme-options.php</code> into which will help keep you file structure nice and tidy.', 0),
(508, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '1ef4770e0f80a3b133e89e6d238ff809', 'Add a variation of the following code to your <code>theme-options.php</code>. You''ll obviously need to fill it in with all your custom array values for contextual help (optional), sections (required), and settings (required).', 0),
(509, 'en', 'theme option-tree', '39bff8432e0a7882ec57904b93b668da', 'The code below is a boilerplate to get your started. For a full list of the available option types click the "Option Types" tab above. Also a quick note, you don''t need to put OptionTree in theme mode to manually create options but you will want to hide the docs and settings as each time you load the admin area the settings be written over with the code below if they''ve changed in any way. However, this ensures your settings do not get tampered with by the end-user.', 0),
