(267, 1, '2013-12-01 08:30:45', '2013-12-01 08:30:45', 'The key framework andprogrammein Bangladesh to address adaptation to climate change are the National AdaptationProgrammeof Action (NAPA) and Bangladesh Climate Change Strategy and Action Plan (BCCSAP). Initiated and partly supported by the UNFCCCsecretariat, all Least Developed Countries (LDC) have been asked to devise the NAPA process and accordingly Bangladesh has developed and submitted the NAPA and progress reports are regularly prepared and submitted to the UNFCC secretariat. Later Bangladesh has developed the BCCSAP in 2008 and revised in 2009 in order tooperationalisethe identified and prioritized adaptation projects and activities under NAPA. DAE and the LACC project are aware of and involved in the development of the NAPA and BCCSAP process. As a part of the regular contribution from the DAE, the project will be very useful in supporting the implementation of the NAPA and BCCSAP priorities in the rural sectors and some critical capacity, knowledge and experience are already being built in previous experiences to feed into and strengthen the NAPA implementation. The government of Bangladesh has acknowledged that the conventional disaster management model focusing on disaster response and rehabilitation must be replaced with a more holistic approach to risk reduction in order to effectively addressvulnerability. The proposed project will under operation following the BCCSAP strategies. Under this project the strategies for adaptation are focused on achieving three related outputs. First, the establishment of climate change adaptation capacity within the partner development Ministries, agencies to fund adaptation related tools, techniques and methods for disaster risk reduction through adaptation activities. In accordance with the outcome improved disaster-proofing of development programming, and enhanced technical capacity toincentivizepositive long-term changes in planning and investment decisions andout putstrengthened DAE and DoF&amp;L livelihood to climate change adaptation capacity MoA/DAE, isdesignatedto deliver different activities to contribute to the overall aim of the project.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dd0b-14yQe4\r\n\r\n[accordion title="Major constraints and challenges"]\r\n\r\nconventional disaster management model focusing on disaster response and rehabilitation must be replaced with a more holistic approach to risk reduction in order to effectively addressvulnerability. The proposed project will under operation following the BCCSAP strategies. Under this project the strategies for adaptation are focused on achieving three related outputs. First, the establishment of climate change adaptation capacity within the partner development Ministries, agencies to fund adaptation related tools, techniques and methods for disaster risk reduction through adaptation activities. In accordance with the outcome improved disaster-proofing of development programming, and enhanced technical capacity toincentivizepositive long-term changes in planning and investment decisions andout putstrengthened DAE and DoF&amp;L livelihood to climate change adaptation capacity MoA/DAE, isdesignatedto deliver different activities to contribute to the overall aim of the project.[/accordion]\r\n\r\n[accordion title="Drought"]\r\n\r\nMany people as well as the government in Bangladesh perceive floods and cyclones as recurrent environmental hazards in the country. They also view that these two hazards are the main contributors to crop loss in the country. But, in reality, droughts afflict the country at least as frequently as do major floods and cyclones, averaging about once in 2.5 years (Adnan, 1993, p. 1; Erickson, 1993, p. 5; Hossain 1990, p. 33). In some years, droughts not only cause a greater damage to crops than floods or cyclones, but they also generally affect more farmers across a wider area (Paul, 1995). If not institutionally and economically tackled, the consequences tend to have a far-reaching effect on the given society, and the socioeconomic problems would assume a chronic pattern. The project will do some special work for drought areas. For mitigation some drought tolerant varieties and effective use of water will guide so. CDMP-II (ComprhensiveDisaster ManagementProgramme) currently running in DAE. The efficient path of this project activity would be helpful to do some intensive work regarding drought mitigation.[/accordion]\r\n\r\n[accordion title="Acidity Problem"]\r\n\r\nAcid sulfate soils (ASSs), which are one of the worst soils in the world, release huge amounts of acid andtoxicallyhigh concentrations of metals, affecting biological activity in the soils as well as in the surrounding water environments (Gosavi et al., 2004; Mathew et al., 2001; Minh et al., 1997; Thawornwong andvanDiest 1974).Acidificationfrom ASSs cause a number of chemical, biological and physical problems arise such as aluminum and iron toxicities, decrease availability of phosphate, nutrient deficiencies, arrested soil ripening, hampered root growth, blockage of drains byochreand corrosion of metal and concrete structures (AARD and LAWOO, 1992). The initial heavy rain on acid sulfate soils cause a first-flush runoff and drainage of toxic water with properties including low pH, low concentration of dissolved oxygen and high concentration of dissolved aluminum which causedmassive fishkill (Anon, 1990; Lin and Melville, 1994). The ASSs cause on- and off- site problems (Ritsema et al., 2000). On-site problems, which have been extensively reviewed (Dent 1986), include Al toxicity in drained soils, Fe and H2S toxicity in flooded soils, salinity and nutrient deficiencies, especiallydecrease availabilityof phosphate. Engineering problems include (i) corrosion of steel and concrete and (ii) uneven subsidence, low bearing strength and fissuring leading to excessive permeability of unripe soils; blockage of drains and filters byochre; and the difficulties of establishing vegetation cover on earthworks and restored land. Off-site problems stem from drainage effluents, earthworks, excavations, and mines. The acid drainage water carries Al released by acid weathering of soil minerals. Our northern part has been sufferingforacidity problems forcoupleof years.Projectwill try to get rid of it through sub-activity Dolomite treatment.[/accordion]', 'The key framework and programme in Bangladesh to address ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '267', '', '', '2013-12-01 08:55:23', '2013-12-01 08:55:23', '', 0, 'http://localhost/iapp/?p=267', 9, 'post', '', 0),
